Concept:  
A compact EVA seat with sports‑camera–style tethers gives astronauts a safe, tool‑anchored way to work around the rings without turning every excursion into a full jet‑chair operation.

Key elements:

Seat frame:

Rigid, lightweight frame that latches to standard hardpoints on rim sections and mods

Fold‑out foot restraints and a simple lap/shoulder harness

Can be parked and left as “EVA work chairs” around the ring

Tether system (sports‑cam style):

Multiple retractable tethers on swiveling mounts, like high‑end action‑camera leashes

One or two body tethers from seat to suit (fail‑safe)

Several tool tethers from seat to tools (no free‑floating hardware)

Auto‑retract with gentle spring force; lockable when extended

Tool cluster on the seat:

Standard sockets, drivers, cutters, cable tools

All on short, retractable tethers

Tools stow into obvious docks so “something missing” is visually obvious

Use pattern:

Astronaut clips suit to seat

Clips seat to structure

Works with both hands free, tools always leashed

Moves seat along the rim as needed, like sliding a mechanic’s stool around a car

Why it fits RAMA:

Simple: No fancy robotics, just tethers, latches, and a frame

Safe: Hard to lose a person or a tool

Standardized: Same seat design works anywhere on any ring

Scalable: You can have dozens of these parked around the structure
A seperate person can activate the tethers to leave the Astronaut free to just do the work
